<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Speaker of India's Parliament, overruling opposition objections, declared 
that the government need not release all sections of a report implicating a 
senior aide to Prime Minister Indira Gandhi in her 1984 assassination. 
Opposition politicians charged that Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi had not 
fulfilled a pledge when on March 27 he released part of the findings from the 
investigation into his mother's death. The document had been suppressed on 
national security grounds since 1986, but publication in an anti-government 
newspaper of allegations concerning aide R. K. Dhawan and a subsequent 
parliamentary uproar compelled Gandhi to try to defuse the dispute. The 
government also said its own inquiry had cleared Dhawan. 
</P>
