<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Energy Secretary James D. Watkins told Congress he expects to give final 
approval by August to a plan for restarting nuclear reactors in South Carolina 
that make materials for atomic weapons. Watkins told a special panel of the 
House Armed Services Committee he had begun reviewing restart recommendations 
from Westinghouse Electric Corp., which operates the Savannah River Site 
reactors near Aiken, S.C., under an Energy Department contract. The three 
reactors, which produce tritium, a radioactive gas used in nuclear warheads, at 
Savannah River have been shut down for nearly a year because of safety 
problems. 
</P>
