<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two Japanese veterans of World War II reportedly will be among the remnants of 
the Communist Party of Malaya who will surrender to Thai forces in the next two 
months, military officials said in Bangkok. An army officer involved in the 
surrender procedure confirmed a report that 15 Japanese war veterans had joined 
the party in 1948 and that two -- both now in their 70s -- had survived 40 
years in the jungle. The party waged a guerrilla war against Japanese troops in 
Malaysia, then fought against the British after the war ended. Their forces 
were eventually defeated, but a few thousand fled to the Thai-Malaysian border 
area, where they have continued to harass both governments for almost four 
decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
