<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Soviet Union permitted 4,240 Jews to emigrate in March, the largest monthly 
total since the benchmark set a decade ago, a leading American Jewish group 
said. This was up from 2,425 in February, when the encouraging trend set 
throughout 1988 and in January showed a drop, and nearly as high as the 4,746 
Jews allowed to emigrate in October, 1979, said a spokesman for the National 
Conference on Soviet Jewry. That last year of the '70s, in which 51,370 Jews 
left the Soviet Union, is the standard for judging emigration rates. It 
compares to 896 in all of 1984 before President Mikhail S. Gorbachev took 
office, and 18,965 in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
