<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION; 
</P>
<P>
CIVILIAN SECRETARIES FOR MILITARY CHOSEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bush Administration has chosen its three civilian service secretaries -- 
Assistant Secretary of Defense Richard L. Armitage for the Army, Undersecretary 
H. Lawrence Garrett III for the Navy and Donald B. Rice of the Rand Corp. for 
the Air Force -- defense officials said. Armitage and Garrett are veteran 
government bureaucrats while Rice is a former government official who has 
stayed in contact with the bureaucracy as a defense specialist at RAND, the 
Washington Post reported. The three must still be formally nominated, then 
confirmed by the Senate, before assuming their duties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA040489-0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 39564 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
April 4, 1989, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
