<HEADLINE>
<P>
TODAY'S CHICAGO RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chicago officials predict that 70% of the 1.56 million voters will cast ballots 
in today's mayoral election. Whites make up 48% of registered voters, blacks 
42% and Latinos 7%. The winner will complete the last two years of the late 
Harold Washington's second term. A poll released Monday by The Daily Chicago 
Southtown Economist and WBBM-TV gave Daley 51% to 35% for Evans and 3% for 
Vrdolyak, with 11% undecided. 
</P>
<P>
TIMOTHY C. EVANS, 45 
</P>
<P>
Independent 
</P>
<P>
Southside alderman 
</P>
<P>
Favored by black voters 
</P>
<P>
RICHARD M. DALEY, 46 
</P>
<P>
Democrat 
</P>
<P>
Defeated incumbent Eugene Sawyer in primary 
</P>
<P>
Cook County prosecutor 
</P>
<P>
EDWARD R. VRDOLYAK, 51 
</P>
<P>
Republican 
</P>
<P>
Former Democrat who opposed Washington in the city council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
