<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
REUTERS TAPS POST PUBLISHER, JUDGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Katharine Graham, publisher of the Washington Post, and a senior British High 
Court judge, Sir Nicolas Browne-Wilkinson, were named today as trustees of 
Reuters. 
</P>
<P>
The 14 trustees' function is to safeguard Reuters' independence and integrity, 
said the chairman of the Reuters Founders Share Co., Lord McGregor of Durris. 
</P>
<P>
Graham, 71, took over the Washington Post media empire in 1963 and put her own 
stamp on the powerful newspaper that exposed the Watergate scandal. 
Browne-Wilkinson, 59, Britain's vice chancellor, lifted a court order in 1987 
that banned three newspapers from publishing extracts from "Spycatcher," the 
memoirs of retired counterintelligence agent Peter Wright. 
</P>
<P>
The Reuters Founders Share Co. controls a "golden share" in Reuters Holdings 
PLC that can overrule other shareholders in the event of a takeover threat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
